Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (peel first if you prefer). When boiling, add the potatoes to the water and cook until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the @lamb mince{200%g} and fry until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

While the mince browns, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces). Quarter the @closed cup mushrooms{150%g}.

Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed and quartered lengthways, then chopped widthways into small pieces). Peeled is not necessary for the carrot.

Once browned, drain and discard any excess fat from the mince. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then transfer to a #bowl{} and set aside.

Pop the pan back on medium-high heat and add the onion, carrot and mushrooms. Fry, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{6-7%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pick the @rosemary{1/2%bunch} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Once the veg has softened, add the mince back to the pan. Stir in the garlic and rosemary and fry until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir the @soy sauce{15%ml} and @tomato puree{30%g} into the pan, then sprinkle over the @plain flour{2%tsp}. Cook, stirring, until well combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Mix in the @water{300%ml} and @chicken stock paste{10%g}. Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the stew has thickened, ~{5-7%minutes}. Add a splash of water if it gets a little too thick.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch}.

Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan, off the heat. Add a knob of @butter{1%knob} and a splash of @milk{15%ml} (if you wish) and mash until smooth with a #potato masher{}.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

When everything's ready, stir half the parsley through the stew.

Share your stew between your #bowls{} with the mash alongside. Sprinkle over the remaining parsley to finish. Enjoy!